The next problem we encounter is the various units included in many of the column-rows such as Mileage, Engine, Power and New_Price and stored as objects. The difficultly with converting these objects to floats, is that objects are not necessarily strings. They can be a mixture of integers, strings and floats, so cannot simply write code to drop the 'km/kg' for example, unless we know for sure that the cells are all floats. Otherwise, it will convert to NaN and we will lose the data. So first, lets check each column and count the types using value_count...

Cleaning Mileage¶

From what we can see in the .head, .tail and .sample, there only appears to be two units for mileage: kmpl and km/kg. There could be other units hidden in the dataframe at such a low frequency that they might have missed them. There are two ways to check. First, we can split the Mileage into two columns, using the space between the numerical value and the units as the break. Second we can run a boolean command which will return any value that is not NaN, or ends with "kmpl" or "km/kg". One limitation of the second method is that if there are a lot of other endings, python will print all of them. Placing a limit on how many python prints, might increase the risk of us missing other units.

Method 1

Creating two columns a temporary dataframe and splitting the Mileage column

In [27]:
def clean_engine(x):
    """ If the value is a string, then remove CC units
    otherwise, the value is numeric and can be converted
    """
    if isinstance(x, str):
        return(x.replace('CC', '').replace(',', ''))
    return(x)

We also have Cr which, according to Google, is short for 'crore' which is equivalent to 100 Lakh. To see if this makes sense, lets examine the car that has a new selling price of 3.75CR...

We can see from the original data, that the used car costing 3.75 Cr is a Bentley, which is an ultra luxury brand. This makes a lot of sense so we can be confident that Cr = 100 Lakh. However, it is problematic to have the New_Price in two different units, so lets convert Cr and Lakh to USD. One April 28, 2021, 1 Indian Ruppee = 0.013 USD. Lets convert the New_Price values to USD

In [45]:
L = 100000 # 100,000 rupees = 1 Lakh
Cr = 100 # 100 Lakh = 1 
USD = 0.013 # 1 rupee = 0.013 USD 

def New_Price_to_dollars(income_val):
    """This function takes in a string representing a price in Lakh or CR
    and converts it to a number. For example, '1.75 Lakh' becomes 2275.
    If the input is already numeric, which probably means it's NaN,
    this function just returns np.nan."""
    if isinstance(income_val, str):  # checks if `income_val` is a string
        multiplier = 1  # handles K vs M salaries
        if income_val.endswith('Lakh'):
            multiplier = L*USD
        elif income_val.endswith('Cr'):
            multiplier = Cr*L*USD
        return float(income_val.replace('Lakh', '').replace('Cr', '')) * multiplier
    else:  # this happens when the current income is np.nan
        return np.nan

UCD['New_Price'] = UCD['New_Price'].apply(New_Price_to_dollars).astype('float')

Part 4: Univariate Data Analysis¶

Note

We are going to revert back to EDA before we continue with the data preprocessing, including dealing with missing values, but we need to know information about specific variables before we can decide where to fill missing values with means or medians, drop them completely, or even scale the data. Therefore, we will conduct univariate data analysis on each variable before deciding how to deal with how we continue to preprocess the data.

In [53]:
def histogram_boxplot(data, xlabel=None, title=None, font_scale=2, figsize=(15,7), bins=None):
    mean = np.mean(data)
    
    sns.set(font_scale=font_scale) # setting the font scale of the seaborn
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.25, .75)}, figsize=figsize)
    sns.boxplot(data, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True,color="violet") #boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value
    sns.distplot(data,kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins,palette="winter") if bins else sns.distplot(data,kde=False, ax=ax_hist2, bins=None)
    ax_hist2.axvline(mean, color='g', linestyle='--') #mean will show as vertical line in the histogram
    if xlabel: ax_hist2.set(xlabel=xlabel) #xlabel
    if title: ax_box2.set(title=title) # title of the graph
    plt.show() # for plotting the graph
In [54]:
def perc_on_bar(plot, feature):
    '''
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function wont work if a colume is passed in hue parameter
    '''
    total = len(feature) # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total) # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.05 # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()           # height of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x,y), size = 20) # annotate the percentage
    plt.show() # shows the plot

We can see there is clearly something wrong. The car is a 2017 model, which means it would have had to be driven more than 2 million km per year for the last three years. # This will loop through and count only cars that are BMW and 2017, and calculate the average KM driven

    if UCD['Name'].loc[index] == 'BMW' and UCD['Year'].loc[index] == 2017:
        counter = counter + 1
        km = km + UCD['Kilometers_Driven'].loc[index]
        
mean_km = ((km - 6500000))/((counter - 1))
print('There are', counter, 'BMWs from 2017 with an average Kilometers Driven of', mean_km)

There are 24 BMWs from 2017 with an average Kilometers Driven of 27743.391304347828

This seems reasonable because it is close to the mean of the 24 BMWs from 2017. We also know that a 2017 vehicle is fairly new and probably didnt have enough time to accumulate as many kms as the median of all cars or of all BMWs.

Mean or Median?

If a variable is normally distributed, the mean, median, (and mode) are approximately the same. Therefore, replacing missing values by the mean and the median are equivalent.

If the variable is skewed, the mean is biased by the values at the far end of the distribution. Therefore, the median is a better representation of the majority of the values in the variable.

Since we know that only one variable (Mileage) has a mostly normal distributions and we know that several of the others (Price, Power, Engine, etc) are heavily skewed, we will replace missing values with the median.

Since our dataframe is a mix of categorical and numerical columns, we cannot replace the missing values with medians in one command since categorical variables do not have medians. So we will replace the numerical columns' missing values one at a time with the column median, and we would then replace categorical missing values with the most frequently recurring variable, however, no categorical variable column has missing values (ignoring New_Price for the time being)

Interestingly enough, the only instances of used cars with Fuel_Type = 'Electric' are the same two instances where mileage is missing. Using our outside knowledge of motor engines, we know that electic engines do not run on gasoline or other liquid fuel so kmpl or km/kg are not good measures. Normally, electric engines are measured by range in km per battery charge, or some similar measure. This, coupled with the fact that there are only 2 instances of electric cars out of a sample of 7253 used cars, means they do not fit this model very well and so we shall just drop these two rows.

Note of Caution:

By dropping the only two rows that contained Fuel_Type = 'Electric', this model will not accurately predict prices of used cars for cars of this fuel type going forward. Management needs to know that they should NOT use this model to try and predict prices for used electric cars in the future. However, due to the incredible small number of Electric cars in this sample, there was a bigger danger in imputing the Mileage of electric cars and including them in the model, and assuming this model would be applicable to used electric cars.

Create Dummy Variables¶

Values like 'Honda' cannot be read into an equation. Simply names to a numerical placeholder will cause our model to place more emphasis on names assigned a higher value. For example, Honda = 1, Toyota = 10. In order to bypass this problem, we can use dummy variables.

Dummy variables ask whether a feature is 'on' or 'off' using 1 for on and 0 for off. For the Transmission column, it will be split into two separate columns, one for Manual and one for Automatic. If the value in the cell was Manual, it will now correspond to a 1 or 'on' in the Manual column while also being 0 or 'off' in the Automatic column.

Model Performance¶

In [224]:
# Mean Absolute Error on test
mean_absolute_error(Y_test, pred)
Out[224]:
3762.9899313318

The mean absolute error (MAE) is the simplest regression error metric to understand. We'll calculate the residual for every data point, taking only the absolute value of each so that negative and positive residuals do not cancel out. We then take the average of all these residuals. Effectively, MAE describes the typical magnitude of the residuals.

In [225]:
# RMSE on test data
mean_squared_error(Y_test, pred)**0.5
Out[225]:
6895.175744551495

The root mean square error (RMSE) is just like the MAE, but squares the difference before summing them all instead of using the absolute value. And then takes the square root of the value.

In [226]:
# R2 Squared: on test
r2_score(Y_test, pred)
Out[226]:
0.7508498139175053

  • R^2 (coefficient of determination) regression score function.

  • Best possible score is 1.0 and it can be negative (because the model can be arbitrarily worse). A constant model that always predicts the expected value of y, disregarding the input features, would get a R^2 score of 0.0.

  • R^2 value is 0.68 which means that in this model independent variables are able to explain 68% of variances in dependent variable

Conclusion¶

  • The Training and testing scores are around 75% and both scores are comparable, hence the model is a good fit.

  • R2_score is 0.75, that explains 75% of total variation in the dataset. So, overall the model is satisfactory.

Part 8: Improving the Model¶

The model is very complex, and this has a lot to do with how many variables are included (54)

We have several strategies to try and reduce the complexity of the model. We can bin like variables, for example we can reduce 10 cities to 4 regions, or 32 different Names into categories. We can also transform some of the values with extreme outliers to log scales, for example, to see if they perform better. We can also drop variables that appear to have high correlations, such as Engine and Power. We will start by making a copy of the dataset in case our model does not improve...

Observation

  • P value of a variable indicates if the variable is significant or not. If we consider significance level to be 0.05 (5%) than any variable with p-values less than 0.05 would be considered significant.
  • Negative values of coefficient shows that, Price deceases with their increase (ie Mileage).
  • Positive values of coefficient shows that, Pricey inceases with their increase (ie Power).
  • Lets check for Multicollinearity which affects the p valuesbefore dealing with the p values directly.

Checking for Multicollinearity¶

We can check for Multicollinearity by looking at the Variance Inflation factors...

Removing Multicollinearity¶

  • To remove multicollinearity
    1. Drop every column one by one, that has VIF score greater than 5.
    2. Look at the adjusted R square of all these models
    3. Drop the Variable that makes least change in Adjusted-R square
    4. Check the VIF Scores again
    5. Continue till you get all VIF scores under 5

We can see Adjusted-R squared for OLSmod3 is : 0.761 while for OLSmod 2 is : 0.751. Dropping engine leaves us with a better model than dropping power.

  • Now the above model only has vifs in the Name variable, but as a categorical variable, I cannot delete one without deleting the whole group. Therefore, I will ignore these variables for now
  • There is no other multicollinearity, so we can look at p values of predictor variables to check their significance

Observations

  • Owner_Type (all columns), have p value greater than 0.05, so they are not significant, we'll drop them since they are a grouped category and either they all stay or they all go
  • But sometimes p values change after dropping a variable, so we'll not drop all variables at once, instead will drop them one by one

TEST FOR NORMALITY¶

What is the test?

  • Error terms/Residuals should be normally distributed

  • It suggests that there are a few unusual data points which must be studied closely to make a better model.

  • Using a QQ Plot, Residuals following normal distribution will make a straight line plot otherwise not.

  • Other test to check for normality : Shapiro-Wilk test.

TEST FOR HOMOSCEDASTICITY¶

  • Test -goldfeldquandt test

  • Homoscedacity - If the variance of the residuals are symmetrically distributed across the regression line , then the data is said to homoscedastic.

  • Heteroscedacity - If the variance is unequal for the residuals across the regression line, then the data is said to be heteroscedastic. In this case the residuals can form an arrow shape or any other non symmetrical shape.

In [285]:

from statsmodels.compat import lzip

lzip(name, test)

[('F statistic', 1.3489468497598258), ('p-value', 3.86167090606552e-14)]

Since p-value > 0.05 we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic. This assumption is therefore valid in the data.

Observations¶

  • Now this is our final model which follows all the assumptions and this can be used for interpretations

        1. The Year variable come out to be very signifcant.  
    2. Power is positively correlated to price, as power goes up, so does the price. 
    3. Kilometers_Driven and Mileage decreases the value of the vehicle
    4. Certain car brands such as Bentley, Lamborghini and LandRover drive the price up, while regular brand cars                      like Nissan and Toyota tend to drive price downwards
    5. Certain cities have different affects on the price, some lower it, others raise it.  This might indicate the                    cost of living in some cities is a lot higher
